    "latex_text": "\\PassOptionsToPackage{numbers}{natbib}\n\\documentclass{article} % For LaTeX2e\n\\usepackage{iclr2024_conference,times}\n\n\\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc} % allow utf-8 input\n\\usepackage[T1]{fontenc}    % use 8-bit T1 fonts\n\\usepackage{hyperref}       % hyperlinks\n\\usepackage{url}            % simple URL typesetting\n\\usepackage{booktabs}       % professional-quality tables\n\\usepackage{amsfonts}       % blackboard math symbols\n\\usepackage{nicefrac}       % compact symbols for 1/2, etc.\n\\usepackage{microtype}      % microtypography\n\\usepackage{titletoc}\n\n\\usepackage{subcaption}\n\\usepackage{graphicx}\n\\usepackage{amsmath}\n\\usepackage{multirow}\n\\usepackage{color}\n\\usepackage{colortbl}\n\\usepackage{cleveref}\n\\usepackage{algorithm}\n\\usepackage{algorithmicx}\n\\usepackage{algpseudocode}\n\\usepackage{tikz}\n\\usepackage{pgfplots}\n\\usepackage{float}\n\\usepackage{array}\n\\usepackage{tabularx}\n\\pgfplotsset{compat=newest}\n\n\n\\DeclareMathOperator*{\\argmin}{arg\\,min}\n\\DeclareMathOperator*{\\argmax}{arg\\,max}\n\n\\graphicspath{{../}} % To reference your generated figures, see below.\n\n\\title{Verified Two-Stage Knowledge Graph Extraction with Low-Cost LLMs for Japanese Document-Level Relation Extraction}\n\n\\author{AIRAS}\n\n\\newcommand{\\fix}{\\marginpar{FIX}}\n\\newcommand{\\new}{\\marginpar{NEW}}\n\n\\begin{document}\n\n\\maketitle\n\n\\begin{abstract}\nLow-cost large language models (LLMs) offer a practical path to rapid knowledge graph construction without training, but in Japanese document-level relation extraction they often produce low-precision outputs when asked to extract all triples in a single pass. This is difficult because documents induce a quadratic space of entity pairs and generative models tend to output plausible yet unsupported relations under one-shot prompting. We introduce a Two-Stage pipeline that separates recall-oriented candidate generation from precision-oriented verification, using structured JSON outputs to make each stage reliably machine-checkable and applying domain and range type constraints as a final consistency filter. We evaluate on 10 documents from the JacRED development set and compare a One-shot baseline to the proposed pipeline across three Gemini Flash family models. Across all logged configurations, the Two-Stage method reduces false positives by about 20–64%, improves precision in every run, and achieves a best F1 of 0.27. Results confirm that verification plus lightweight constraints materially improves reliability for budget DocRE, while recall (0.12–0.22) remains the main bottleneck.\n\\end{abstract}\n\n\\section{Introduction}\n\\label{sec:intro}\nDocument-level relation extraction (DocRE) seeks to identify semantic relations between entities when the evidence for a fact may be distributed across multiple sentences. This capability is a core ingredient for building knowledge graphs from text, where downstream applications such as search and question answering depend on extracted facts being both correct (precision) and sufficiently comprehensive (recall). The DocRED benchmark crystallized why the task is intrinsically difficult: a substantial fraction of relational facts require multi-sentence reading and reasoning, and evaluation frameworks increasingly emphasize that predicted relations should be supported by explicit evidence in the document \\cite{yao-2019-docred}. Subsequent syntheses of the field highlight additional challenges that become acute at document scale, including aliasing and coreference, long-context modeling, and, critically, the quadratic explosion of candidate entity pairs that must be considered even before reasoning about relation labels \\cite{delaunay-2023-comprehensive}.\n\nJapanese DocRE adds both practical urgency and methodological complexity. JacRED was introduced as a native Japanese Wikipedia DocRE benchmark with evidence sentences, motivated by limitations of translation-based transfer from English corpora and by the need to evaluate on documents that reflect Japanese-specific surface phenomena and topic distributions \\cite{ma-2024-building}. Beyond providing data, JacRED reports that in-context learning with large language models performs poorly under their DocRE evaluation protocol, underscoring a gap between general-purpose generation and reliable, evidence-grounded structured extraction in Japanese \\cite{ma-2024-building}.\n\nIn parallel, practitioners increasingly turn to low-cost LLMs as ``drop-in'' information extraction engines because they can be deployed quickly and do not require task-specific training. Yet this convenience comes with a recurring reliability problem: when prompted to output structured records, LLMs may produce hallucinated or weakly supported items, and such over-generation is especially pronounced when the instruction implicitly asks the model to be exhaustive \\cite{xu-2023-large}. In DocRE, this reliability issue interacts with the combinatorics of the task. A one-shot prompt that requests all entity--relation triples forces a single generation step to simultaneously search the large candidate space, perform cross-sentence reasoning, and calibrate outputs so that only text-supported relations are returned. When this coupling fails, the most visible symptom is a surge of false positives: relations that are plausible given world knowledge or local co-occurrence, but not actually supported by the document.\n\nThis paper evaluates the hypothesis that low-cost LLM-based knowledge graph extraction for Japanese DocRE suffers from low precision primarily due to false positives induced by one-shot extraction. We argue that the root cause is structural: one-shot extraction couples a recall objective (``find as many relations as possible'') with a precision objective (``only output what is supported'') in the same decoding process. Our response is a simple but effective decomposition.\n\nWe propose a Two-Stage approach that cleanly separates recall-oriented candidate generation from precision-oriented verification. In Stage 1, the model is instructed to be inclusive and to output a set of relation candidates in a structured JSON schema. In Stage 2, the model is asked to verify each candidate, in batches, by deciding whether the relation is supported by the document context. Finally, a deterministic post-processing step filters verified candidates using domain and range type constraints as a lightweight consistency check.\n\nWe test the approach with an empirical comparison on 10 documents sampled from the JacRED development set \\cite{ma-2024-building}. We compare a One-shot baseline against the proposed pipeline across three Gemini Flash family models (Gemini 2.0 Flash, Gemini 2.5 Flash, and Gemini 3 Flash Preview). For each run we report micro-averaged precision, recall, and F1 over relation triples, along with counts of true positives, false positives, and false negatives.\n\nOur contributions are:\n- We characterize one-shot, low-cost LLM DocRE in Japanese as primarily failing through false-positive over-generation, motivating decomposition rather than purely prompt-level fixes.\n- We introduce a practical Two-Stage extraction pipeline using structured JSON outputs for both candidate generation and verification, plus deterministic type-constraint filtering.\n- We provide a controlled empirical comparison on 10 JacRED dev documents across multiple Gemini Flash configurations, showing consistent false-positive reductions of approximately 20–64% and corresponding precision gains.\n- We analyze remaining limitations, especially the persistently low recall (0.12–0.22), and outline prompt- and data-centric avenues to improve coverage while preserving precision gains.\n\nThe broader implication is that verification-oriented pipelines can make budget LLMs more usable for DocRE-style knowledge graph construction, even when absolute performance remains far from supervised DocRE systems. Improving recall without reintroducing false positives appears to be the main next step, potentially via more effective candidate generation prompts and better alignment between verification decisions and evidence selection, as emphasized in DocRE benchmarks \\cite{yao-2019-docred,ma-2024-building}.\n\n\\section{Related Work}\n\\label{sec:related}\nOur work connects to three lines of research: document-level relation extraction (as a task and benchmark family), Japanese DocRE resources, and reliability techniques for LLM-based generative information extraction.\n\nDocRE benchmarks and modeling approaches. DocRED established a widely adopted formulation for document-level relation extraction, highlighting that many relations require multi-sentence evidence and motivating evaluation protocols centered on micro-averaged precision, recall, and F1, alongside evidence annotations for interpretability and accountability \\cite{yao-2019-docred}. The DocRE literature surveyed by Delaunay et al. emphasizes that most high-performing systems explicitly address candidate explosion and cross-sentence reasoning through specialized architectures such as graph-based message passing, entity-centric representations, and tailored pooling or thresholding strategies \\cite{delaunay-2023-comprehensive}. Compared with that body of work, our approach differs in assumptions and optimization targets: we do not train task-specific DocRE models and therefore do not adopt supervised architectures designed to maximize overall F1 on large benchmarks. Instead, we study a training-free, low-cost LLM pipeline where reliability (precision) is the central constraint, and where the main degree of freedom is how the extraction task is decomposed into model calls.\n\nJapanese DocRE datasets and evaluation context. JacRED provides a native Japanese Wikipedia DocRE benchmark with evidence sentences and a relation schema, motivated by the limited generalization of translation-based transfer from English DocRE corpora to native Japanese text \\cite{ma-2024-building}. For our purposes, JacRED's evidence-centered annotation and its findings on weak LLM in-context performance help motivate why naive prompting is insufficient. However, our evaluation setting differs from typical JacRED modeling work: rather than training supervised models on the full train split, we evaluate a small subset (10 dev documents) to isolate the effect of a pipeline intervention (One-shot versus Two-Stage verification). As a result, supervised methods that rely on extensive training data and model engineering are not directly comparable within our cost and deployment constraints.\n\nLLM-based generative IE and structured output reliability. The survey of LLMs for generative information extraction documents a range of techniques for improving faithfulness and robustness, including prompt engineering, structured output formats, constrained decoding, and verification or self-correction loops \\cite{xu-2023-large}. Our Two-Stage design aligns with the general reliability pattern of proposal followed by validation, but operationalizes it in a DocRE setting where candidate generation must explore a large combinatorial space. Separately, work on generating structured outputs from language models studies schema-constrained decoding for JSON and emphasizes compliance and coverage as first-class concerns \\cite{geng-2025-generating}. While our experiments rely on the Gemini API's structured-output mechanism (rather than the open-source engines compared in that work), the motivation is shared: schema compliance enables deterministic parsing and reduces the brittleness of downstream processing. Our contribution is not a new constraint engine; rather, it is a task decomposition that uses structured outputs in both stages and combines verification with domain and range type constraints to reduce false positives.\n\nJoint extraction versus pipeline decomposition. End-to-end joint modeling of named entity recognition and relation extraction has been shown to reduce pipeline error propagation in sentence-level settings by training a single model that predicts entities and relations together \\cite{giorgi-2019-end}. That line of work is complementary but not directly applicable to our setting for two reasons. First, it assumes supervised training and task-specific architectures, whereas we focus on a training-free pipeline using low-cost LLM calls. Second, the cited joint approaches are typically designed for intra-sentence extraction, while DocRE requires document-level context and often multi-sentence reasoning. Our work therefore explores an alternative trade-off: rather than coupling tasks through end-to-end learning, we couple them through explicit verification stages that aim to improve precision under deployment constraints.\n\nIn summary, prior work motivates the central pressures we address: evidence-grounded extraction at document scale, Japanese-specific evaluation needs, and the reliability challenges of generative IE. Our study contributes empirical evidence that verification-based decomposition can substantially reduce false positives in Japanese DocRE when using budget LLMs.\n\n\\section{Background}\n\\label{sec:background}\nDocument-level relation extraction and evaluation. DocRE formalizes relation extraction over documents in which entities may be mentioned multiple times and supporting evidence may span sentences. DocRED popularized this setting and emphasized evaluation centered on micro-averaged precision, recall, and F1 over relation instances, complemented in some settings by variants such as ``Ign'' metrics and evidence-related measures \\cite{yao-2019-docred}. JacRED follows the DocRE paradigm for Japanese Wikipedia and provides sentence-level evidence annotations, reinforcing a key constraint that shapes our design: correct relations should be supported by the document text rather than inferred solely from plausibility \\cite{ma-2024-building}.\n\nProblem setting and notation. We consider a document d. Let E(d) denote its set of entities. The relation schema is a fixed set of directed relation labels R. A predicted relation instance is a triple (h, r, t), where h is a head entity in E(d), t is a tail entity in E(d), and r is a label in R. Let G(d) be the gold set of relation triples for d, and P(d) be the set predicted by a system. Over an evaluation set of documents, we compute micro-precision as |P \\cap G| / |P|, micro-recall as |P \\cap G| / |G|, and micro-F1 as 2PR/(P+R), where P and R denote the micro-precision and micro-recall values, respectively.\n\nWhy one-shot prompting is brittle in DocRE. The DocRE survey literature emphasizes that the number of ordered entity pairs grows quadratically with |E(d)|, which makes exhaustive consideration of candidate pairs expensive and increases the chance of spurious predictions if a model is encouraged to be exhaustive \\cite{delaunay-2023-comprehensive}. In a one-shot prompting regime, an LLM must implicitly perform candidate search, evidence assessment, and calibration in a single generation. Generative IE studies report that such settings are prone to hallucinated structured outputs and are highly sensitive to prompt design and output formatting \\cite{xu-2023-large}.\n\nStructured outputs and deterministic post-processing. A practical obstacle in LLM-based extraction is output brittleness: unconstrained generation often violates the intended schema, forcing ad hoc parsing. Structured outputs and constrained decoding address this by forcing the model's output to comply with a JSON schema, improving robustness and enabling deterministic validation and processing \\cite{geng-2025-generating}. In our work, structured outputs serve two roles: they reduce parsing failures and they make it feasible to pipeline LLM calls by passing machine-readable candidate sets into verification.\n\nType constraints as lightweight consistency checks. Knowledge graph schemas often imply domain and range constraints for relations: particular relation labels are only meaningful for certain types of head and tail entities. While our pipeline's type system is implementation-defined and not formalized beyond its use as a post-processing rule set, we use the general notion of domain and range filtering: after verification, we remove triples that violate predefined permissible combinations of (type(h), r, type(t)). This step is intended to further reduce false positives without additional model calls.\n\nAssumptions. Our setting assumes access to the entity list per document (as provided by the dataset), a fixed relation schema, and the ability to call a low-cost LLM multiple times per document to support verification. We explicitly prioritize precision improvements as a practical requirement for downstream knowledge graph construction, even when recall remains modest.\n\n\\section{Method}\n\\label{sec:method}\nWe propose Two-Stage KG Extraction, a training-free pipeline for Japanese document-level relation extraction that separates recall-oriented exploration from precision-oriented validation. The pipeline comprises (i) candidate generation, (ii) candidate verification, and (iii) deterministic type-constraint filtering. The central design principle is objective separation: the first stage is encouraged to cover possibilities (high recall pressure), while the second stage is instructed to be conservative and evidence-focused (high precision pressure).\n\nStage 1: recall-oriented candidate generation. For a given document d and its entity set E(d), Stage 1 prompts a low-cost LLM to produce a candidate set C(d) of relation triples (h, r, t). The prompt explicitly encourages inclusiveness in proposing relations that might be supported somewhere in the document. Candidates are emitted in a structured JSON format so they can be parsed deterministically and passed into the next stage without brittle heuristics. This design is motivated by work on structured-output generation, which shows that schema compliance is essential for reliable downstream consumption \\cite{geng-2025-generating}.\n\nStage 2: precision-oriented verification. Stage 2 receives C(d) and asks the LLM to decide, for each candidate c in C(d), whether the relation is supported by the document context. Verification is performed in batches to reduce the number of API calls. The verifier outputs a structured JSON object containing a binary supported or not-supported decision per candidate. Conceptually, the verifier implements a filter that targets the main failure mode of one-shot extraction: hallucinated or merely plausible relations. This proposal-then-validate pattern is widely discussed in the generative IE literature as a pragmatic approach to improving faithfulness without supervised fine-tuning \\cite{xu-2023-large}. Let V(d) be the subset of C(d) that passes verification.\n\nType-constraint filtering. After verification, we apply a deterministic post-processing step that enforces domain and range constraints associated with relation labels. For each verified triple (h, r, t), we check whether the tuple (type(h), r, type(t)) is allowed under predefined constraints. Triples that violate constraints are removed. This filter provides a lightweight final guard against inconsistent outputs and further reduces false positives.\n\nFinal prediction. The output set of predicted triples is P(d) = FilterTypes(V(d)).\n\nRationale. One-shot extraction implicitly merges two competing requirements: it must explore a large candidate space driven by the quadratic number of entity pairs and simultaneously avoid outputting unsupported relations. The Two-Stage pipeline externalizes the second requirement into an explicit decision step applied to concrete candidates. This is particularly relevant for DocRE because candidate explosion can dominate error profiles and because evidence for correct relations may be distributed across sentences, increasing the risk that a generative model fills gaps with plausible completions if not explicitly constrained \\cite{delaunay-2023-comprehensive}.\n\nImplementation scope. The method is implemented as a Gemini API-based pipeline using structured outputs for both generation and verification, followed by post-processing with type constraints. The pipeline introduces no learned parameters; all changes are at the level of task decomposition, prompting, and deterministic filtering.\n\n\\section{Experimental Setup}\n\\label{sec:experimental}\nDataset and sample. We evaluate on 10 documents from the JacRED development set, a Japanese Wikipedia DocRE benchmark that includes relation labels and sentence-level evidence annotations \\cite{ma-2024-building}. The goal of this evaluation is not to establish a new benchmark-level result, but to test whether pipeline decomposition reduces false positives under a realistic, low-cost LLM deployment scenario.\n\nModels and configurations. We use three models from the Gemini Flash family: Gemini 2.0 Flash, Gemini 2.5 Flash, and Gemini 3 Flash Preview. For Gemini 2.5 Flash and Gemini 3 Flash Preview, we evaluate two logged configurations labeled ``off'' and ``2048''. For Gemini 2.0 Flash, we evaluate one configuration labeled ``none''. The available context does not define what these configuration labels correspond to internally; we therefore treat them strictly as distinct experimental settings recorded in the logs.\n\nCompared methods. We compare two extraction strategies under each model configuration.\n\nBaseline: One-shot Extraction. A single LLM call is used to extract entities and relations in one step, returning a set of relation triples.\n\nProposed: Two-Stage KG Extraction. Stage 1 generates relation candidates. Stage 2 verifies candidates in batches. A final post-processing step applies domain and range type constraints.\n\nMetrics. We report micro-averaged precision, recall, and F1 over relation triples across the 10 documents. We also report the underlying contingency counts: true positives (tp), false positives (fp), and false negatives (fn). These counts reflect the evaluation script's matching procedure between predicted and gold triples.\n\nImplementation details and constraints. The experiments are executed using a Gemini API-based pipeline with structured outputs. The code path includes candidate generation, candidate verification, and type-constraint post-processing. No supervised training, fine-tuning, or hyperparameter search is performed.\n\nExecution environment. Runs are conducted using a runner configuration described only as executing Gemini API calls on local or cloud infrastructure. In keeping with the available evidence, we do not report or assume hardware specifications.\n\nFairness considerations. For each model configuration, Baseline and Proposed methods are evaluated on the same 10 documents and scored with the same evaluation code. Because the Two-Stage method requires additional LLM calls for verification, we focus the comparison on extraction quality (precision, recall, F1, and error counts). Runtime and monetary cost measurements are not available in the provided logs, and we therefore do not report them.\n\n\\section{Results}\n\\label{sec:results}\nWe report all logged results comparing One-shot Extraction (Baseline) to Two-Stage KG Extraction (Proposed) on 10 JacRED dev documents. The context includes no figures; therefore, results are presented as narrative and tables only.\n\nExperiment 1: Gemini 2.0 Flash (configuration: none). Baseline achieves precision 0.20, recall 0.15, and F1 0.17, with tp = 22, fp = 86, fn = 126. Proposed improves precision to 0.35 and recall to 0.19, achieving F1 0.25 with tp = 28, fp = 51, fn = 121. False positives decrease by 35 (from 86 to 51), corresponding to a 40.7% reduction, while true positives increase by 6.\n\nExperiment 2: Gemini 2.5 Flash (configuration: off). Baseline achieves precision 0.17, recall 0.16, and F1 0.17, with tp = 24, fp = 115, fn = 124. Proposed increases precision to 0.30 but reduces recall to 0.12, yielding F1 0.17 with tp = 18, fp = 42, fn = 130. False positives decrease by 73 (from 115 to 42), a 63.5% reduction. However, true positives decrease by 6, offsetting gains in precision so that F1 remains unchanged.\n\nExperiment 3: Gemini 2.5 Flash (configuration: 2048). Baseline achieves precision 0.18, recall 0.17, and F1 0.17, with tp = 25, fp = 115, fn = 123. Proposed improves precision to 0.36 and recall to 0.21, achieving F1 0.27 with tp = 31, fp = 54, fn = 117. False positives decrease by 61 (from 115 to 54), a 53.0% reduction, and true positives increase by 6.\n\nExperiment 4: Gemini 3 Flash Preview (configuration: off). Baseline achieves precision 0.26, recall 0.16, and F1 0.20, with tp = 24, fp = 70, fn = 124. Proposed improves precision to 0.36 and recall to 0.22, achieving F1 0.27 with tp = 32, fp = 56, fn = 116. False positives decrease by 14 (from 70 to 56), a 20.0% reduction, and true positives increase by 8.\n\nExperiment 5: Gemini 3 Flash Preview (configuration: 2048). Baseline achieves precision 0.31, recall 0.22, and F1 0.26, with tp = 33, fp = 74, fn = 115. Proposed yields precision 0.37, recall 0.20, and F1 0.26, with tp = 30, fp = 52, fn = 118. False positives decrease by 22 (from 74 to 52), a 29.7% reduction. True positives decrease by 3, leading to no net gain in F1.\n\nCross-run summary and error profile. Across all five logged comparisons, the Two-Stage pipeline reduces false positives, with reductions ranging from 20.0% to 63.5%. Precision improves in every run, moving from a baseline range of 0.17--0.31 to a proposed range of 0.30--0.37. F1 improves in three configurations (Gemini 2.0 Flash none, Gemini 2.5 Flash 2048, and Gemini 3 Flash Preview off) and matches baseline in two configurations (Gemini 2.5 Flash off and Gemini 3 Flash Preview 2048). The best observed F1 is 0.27, achieved in two runs: Gemini 2.5 Flash (2048) Proposed and Gemini 3 Flash Preview (off) Proposed.\n\nImportantly, recall remains low across all settings, ranging from 0.12 to 0.22. This pattern aligns with the accompanying analysis report indicating that, while verification is effective at suppressing false positives, overall coverage is limited and likely constrained by the candidate generation stage and/or conservative verification decisions.\n\nTable 1: All metrics and counts.\n- Gemini 2.0 Flash none: Baseline P/R/F1 = 0.20/0.15/0.17 (tp 22, fp 86, fn 126); Proposed 0.35/0.19/0.25 (tp 28, fp 51, fn 121).\n- Gemini 2.5 Flash off: Baseline 0.17/0.16/0.17 (tp 24, fp 115, fn 124); Proposed 0.30/0.12/0.17 (tp 18, fp 42, fn 130).\n- Gemini 2.5 Flash 2048: Baseline 0.18/0.17/0.17 (tp 25, fp 115, fn 123); Proposed 0.36/0.21/0.27 (tp 31, fp 54, fn 117).\n- Gemini 3 Flash Preview off: Baseline 0.26/0.16/0.20 (tp 24, fp 70, fn 124); Proposed 0.36/0.22/0.27 (tp 32, fp 56, fn 116).\n- Gemini 3 Flash Preview 2048: Baseline 0.31/0.22/0.26 (tp 33, fp 74, fn 115); Proposed 0.37/0.20/0.26 (tp 30, fp 52, fn 118).\n\n\\section{Conclusion}\n\\label{sec:conclusion}\nLow-cost LLMs can simplify deployment for knowledge graph construction, but our results show that one-shot extraction is unreliable for Japanese document-level relation extraction due to a large number of false positive relations. We addressed this by introducing a Two-Stage pipeline that separates recall-oriented candidate generation from precision-oriented verification, uses structured JSON outputs to ensure deterministic parsing across stages, and applies domain and range type constraints as a final consistency filter.\n\nOn 10 documents from the JacRED development set, evaluated across Gemini 2.0 Flash, Gemini 2.5 Flash, and Gemini 3 Flash Preview configurations, the Two-Stage method consistently reduced false positives by 20.0% to 63.5% and improved precision in every run. F1 improved in three of five configurations and matched the baseline in the remaining two, with the best observed F1 reaching 0.27. These outcomes support the central thesis that explicit verification and lightweight constraints are effective levers for making budget LLM DocRE more dependable.\n\nThe dominant remaining limitation is recall, which stays low (0.12--0.22) across all settings. Future work should therefore focus on improving candidate generation coverage while preserving verification as a guardrail, for example through prompt refinement and the introduction of few-shot examples, and by exploring closer alignment between verification and evidence selection as emphasized in DocRE benchmarks.\n\nThis work was generated by \\textsc{AIRAS} \\citep{airas2025}.\n\n\\bibliographystyle{iclr2024_conference}\n\\bibliography{references}\n\n\\end{document}",
